≫9.@@

  sisobus
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Wind speed demo (≫ GUST / ≪ CALM, SPEC §3.7).

  Run this two ways and compare the output:

      windy run      examples/gust.wnd    → "0 "  (default v1.0)
      windy run --v0 examples/gust.wnd    → "9 "  + warning to stderr

  The exact same source produces a different result because ≫ and ≪
  are NOT v0.4 opcodes. With --v0 (legacy gate) they're "unknown
  glyphs" — the runtime warns once and treats them as NOPs. Without
  --v0 (default) they manage the IP's per-tick speed.

  Tick by tick on row 0 (default v1.0):

    cell        op                         speed   IP after move
    ----        ------------------------   -----   -------------
    (0,0) ≫     GUST: speed += 1            2      (2,0)
    (1,0) 9     SKIPPED (intermediate)      —      —
    (2,0) .     pop empty stack → "0 "      2      (4,0)
    (3,0) @     SKIPPED (intermediate)      —      —
    (4,0) @     HALT                        —      —

  At speed N the IP advances N cells per tick; only the destination
  cell decodes — intermediate cells are not even read for unknown-
  glyph warnings or string-mode toggles. Fast wind blows past
  obstacles, including the digit 9 here, so `.` finds an empty stack
  and prints the underflow zero.

  Compare with v0.4 legacy (same source, with --v0):

    cell    op                                output
    ----    -----------------------------     ------
    (0,0)   ≫ unknown — warned, NOP           (warning on stderr)
    (1,0)   9 push                            —
    (2,0)   .  pop & print                    "9 "
    (3,0)   @ HALT                            —

  Things to play with:

    - Add a CALM (≪) somewhere on the path; speed drops back. Note
      that ≪ at speed 1 traps the program (exit 134) — that's a
      design choice to give ≪ a sharp edge instead of a silent clamp.

    - Layout cells so the IP hits ≫ multiple times. Each ≫ adds 1 to
      speed; the IP starts skipping more aggressively each tick.

    - Try speed=3 / speed=4 traversals — at higher speeds the
      probability that any given decoration cell ever runs drops
      sharply. Lay your "real" code on a dense grid of multiples of
      the active speed.
